{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture programming in the 1960s: like a massive cookbook with endless recipes. You'd write step-by-step instructions in one giant list. It worked for simple dishes, but try cooking a feast for thousands? Chaos in the kitchen.",
      "title": "Code as Endless Recipes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Programs ballooned into monsters. Code twisted like spaghetti on a plate—change one noodle, and the whole mess unraveled. Bugs hid everywhere, maintenance felt like herding cats, and teams drowned in frustration.",
      "title": "The Spaghetti Code Mess"
    },
    {
      "text": "What if code mirrored real life? Enter Norwegian pioneers Kristen Nygaard and Ole-Johan Dahl in 1967. They invented 'objects'—self-contained bundles of data and actions, like a car with its engine, wheels, and drive button.",
      "title": "Objects Mimic the Real World"
    },
    {
      "text": "Their Simula language was the spark. Objects could inherit traits, like a sports car getting a sedan’s comfy seats. Reuse code without copying! It was a game-changer for simulations, but the world was ready for more.",
      "title": "Simula Lights the Fuse"
    },
    {
      "text": "Alan Kay at Xerox PARC took it further with Smalltalk in the 1970s. Everything became an object—even numbers and code itself! Pure, elegant OOP: classes as blueprints, objects as living copies. Minds blown.",
      "title": "Smalltalk Makes It Pure"
    },
    {
      "text": "OOP swept through languages like C++, Java, Python. Software exploded: reusable blocks built empires. Games with smart characters, apps that scale seamlessly—all thanks to organizing code like Lego bricks.",
      "title": "Building Software Empires"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, OOP is the backbone of modern programming. It tames complexity, boosts teamwork, and lets you create worlds in code. Mastering its principles? You're unlocking the secret to writing software that lasts.",
      "title": "Why OOP Rules Your Code"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a world where math froze time. Geometry sketched perfect circles and triangles, algebra solved steady equations. But motion? A cannonball's arc or a planet's whirl? Math shrugged helplessly.",
      "title": "Math's Static World"
    },
    {
      "text": "Galileo rolled balls down ramps, timing their speed. Kepler mapped Mars' quirky orbit. Both screamed for a tool to capture instant change — the speed 'right now,' not averaged over time.",
      "title": "Scientists' Motion Headache"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hints flickered in antiquity. Archimedes crammed tiny triangles under curves to guess areas. It worked-ish, but slicing reality thinner and thinner? Pure drudgery, no elegant formula.",
      "title": "Clumsy Ancient Hacks"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter Isaac Newton, pondering a falling apple. What if change flows continuously, like water? He forged 'fluxions' — math to track rates of change in the blink of an eye.",
      "title": "Newton's Apple Epiphany"
    },
    {
      "text": "Meanwhile, Gottfried Leibniz scribbled across Europe. His 'infinitesimals' — vanishingly small slices — unlocked accumulation. Together, they birthed calculus amid a bitter priority feud.",
      "title": "Leibniz's Infinite Insight"
    },
    {
      "text": "Boom! Derivatives nailed instantaneous speed. Integrals tallied total distance. Physics exploded: gravity laws, orbital mechanics. Engineering leaped from hunch to precision.",
      "title": "Calculus Unleashes Motion"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, it's your secret weapon. GPS plots your path, economists predict markets, doctors model heartbeats. Calculus turns chaotic change into predictable power.",
      "title": "Why Calculus Powers Now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine a world where every creature was perfectly crafted by divine hands—no changes, no adaptations, just God's eternal blueprint locked in place for millennia.",
      "title": "Species Set in Stone"
    },
    {
      "text": "But then fossils turned up: massive bones of beasts long gone, sea creatures fossilized on mountaintops. Extinctions? Why would perfection vanish? Nature's puzzle begged for answers.",
      "title": "Fossils That Defied Faith"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, betting animals evolved by sheer willpower—giraffes stretching necks longer, passing the trait to kids. A stretchy idea, but it didn't quite hold up.",
      "title": "Lamarck's Neck-Stretching Dream"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cue Charles Darwin, a curious 22-year-old, puking his guts out on the HMS Beagle. Sailing the globe from 1831, he sketched endless variations in birds, plants, and beasts.",
      "title": "Darwin's Seasick Odyssey"
    },
    {
      "text": "Galapagos Islands stole the show: finches everywhere, each with beaks custom-tooled like Swiss Army knives—for seeds, bugs, or cactus. Same bird family, wildly different lives.",
      "title": "Finches in Disguise"
    },
    {
      "text": "Home pondering, Darwin read Malthus: populations explode, but food doesn't—fierce competition! Variations mean some thrive, breed more. Boom: natural selection, nature's survival contest.",
      "title": "Nature's Ruthless Audition"
    },
    {
      "text": "After decades of doubt, 1859's 'On the Origin of Species' dropped like a bomb. Species branch like a family tree, evolving over eons through tiny tweaks and big pressures.",
      "title": "The Book That Rewrote Life"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, evolution arms us against superbugs, shapes vaccines, reveals our ape cousins. It's the backbone of biology, explaining life's wild diversity and our spot in it.",
      "title": "Why Evolution Shapes You"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine ancient gatherings: philosophers shouting in the marketplace, each claiming truth. But without rules, it's chaos—who's right? The loudest voice wins, not the soundest reason.",
      "title": "Debates Without Referees"
    },
    {
      "text": "Life ran on myths, omens, and hunches. Kings declared war on bad advice, cities crumbled from faulty plans. Thinking was a wild river, flooding with errors and no banks to guide it.",
      "title": "The Perils of Gut Thinking"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter the seekers: Socrates poked holes in assumptions, asking 'Why believe that?' Plato dreamed of ideal truths. But questions swirled like smoke—needed solid ground.",
      "title": "The Spark of Inquiry"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aristotle, the great organizer, changed everything. Like a chef perfecting a recipe, he broke arguments into ingredients: premises leading inevitably to conclusions via syllogisms.",
      "title": "Aristotle's Logical Kitchen"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, thinking had rails. 'All men are mortal, Socrates is a man, so...' Boom—proof! Logic spread like wildfire, fueling science, law, and discovery.",
      "title": "The Syllogism Revolution"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, every app you use, every court verdict, every scientific breakthrough rests on these ancient rules. Logic: your shield against nonsense in a noisy world.",
      "title": "Logic's Living Legacy"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine ir ao mercado toda semana com a mesma nota no bolso. De repente, seu pão, leite e feijão custam mais. Sua nota compra menos. Essa sensação frustrante é a inflação batendo à porta, como um ladrão silencioso roubando o valor do seu dinheiro.",
      "title": "O Ladrão Silencioso do Bolso"
    },
    {
      "text": "Antes do dinheiro, as trocas eram diretas: trocava galinhas por ferramentas. Preços fixos, sem surpresas. Mas com o surgimento das moedas, veio a magia – e o problema. Reis antigos derretiam ouro e prata, misturando metal barato para cunhar mais moedas.",
      "title": "Das Trocas ao Ouro Falso"
    },
    {
      "text": "Resultado? Mais moedas circulando, mas a mesma quantidade de pães e tecidos. Preços subiam como bolhas de sabão inflando. No Império Romano, isso gerava revoltas; na França do século XVIII, caos total.",
      "title": "Moedas Vazias, Preços nas Alturas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pule para o Brasil dos anos 80: preços mudavam de hora em hora! Seu salário virava pó antes do fim do mês. Gente acordava de madrugada para comprar antes que tudo encarecesse mais. Hiperinflação, o monstro devorador.",
      "title": "O Pesadelo Brasileiro"
    },
    {
      "text": "O que mudou tudo? Economistas descobriram: inflação é demais dinheiro perseguindo poucos bens. Como uma festa onde todos pedem pizza, mas só há uma – o preço explode.",
      "title": "A Fórmula da Explosão"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoje, bancos centrais como o BC vigiam isso de perto, ajustando a 'impressora de dinheiro'. Sem controle, sua poupança evapora; com ele, seu futuro cresce. Entender inflação é como ter um mapa para navegar na economia.",
      "title": "Por Que Cuidar Disso Hoje"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagina un mundo donde una manzana cae porque 'quiere' volver al centro de la Tierra, como un pez al agua. Así explicaban los antiguos por qué las cosas caen, pero ¿y los planetas danzando en el cielo? Eran esferas de cristal girando en armonía perfecta.",
      "title": "Un mundo de mitos y misterios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aristóteles, el sabio griego, decía que todo tiene un lugar natural: la tierra abajo, el fuego arriba. Las piedras caen rápido porque son pesadas, las plumas lento porque son ligeras. Sonaba lógico, ¿no? Pero no explicaba por qué una piedra lanzada sigue volando un rato.",
      "title": "Aristóteles y el orden natural"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los planetas eran el gran enigma. ¿Por qué Marte retrocede a veces? Los astrónomos medievales imaginaban ruedas dentro de ruedas, como un reloj loco. Nada unía la caída de una hoja con el baile de Júpiter. El universo parecía dos mundos separados.",
      "title": "El rompecabezas celeste"
    },
    {
      "text": "Llega Galileo, subiendo a la torre de Pisa. Tira bolas de diferente peso: ¡caen igual de rápido! Ignorando el aire, todo acelera parejo. '¡El movimiento es más simple de lo que pensábamos!', grita. Desafía siglos de dogma con experimentos caseros.",
      "title": "Galileo y la torre rebelde"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mientras, Kepler observa el cielo con telescopio. Descubre que los planetas viajan en elipses, no círculos perfectos. Tres leyes mágicas: órbitas elípticas, barridos iguales, armonía musical. Pero ¿qué fuerza los mantiene en pista, como autos en una pista ovalada?",
      "title": "Kepler dibuja elipses"
    },
    {
      "text": "Isaac Newton, soñando bajo un manzano, ve caer una fruta. '¡Si la gravedad tira la manzana, también debe jalar la Luna!', piensa. Une la Tierra con los cielos en una sola ley: toda masa atrae a toda masa con fuerza inversa al cuadrado de la distancia. ¡Boom!",
      "title": "Newton y la manzana iluminadora"
    },
    {
      "text": "De golpe, todo encaja: manzanas, proyectiles, planetas, mareas. La gravedad es universal, como un imán gigante invisible conectando el cosmos. Newton publica en 1687, y el mundo nunca vuelve a ser el mismo.",
      "title": "La ley que unió el universo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoy, esa idea lanza cohetes a Marte, calcula órbitas de satélites para tu GPS y explica por qué no flotamos en el espacio. Entender la gravedad es entender por qué el universo baila en armonía, y tú eres parte del baile.",
      "title": "Por qué la gravedad te cambia la vida"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture the 1950s: AI dreamed of chatting like humans. But early systems were like strict librarians enforcing rigid rules—if a sentence didn't match the if-then cookbook, it crashed. No room for slang, puns, or poetry.",
      "title": "AI's Rule-Bound Infancy"
    },
    {
      "text": "Human language is a wild river—twisting with sarcasm, context, idioms. 'Bank' could mean money or a river edge. Rule-based AI drowned in this chaos, spitting out nonsense 90% of the time. Conversations? Forget it.",
      "title": "Language's Slippery Chaos"
    },
    {
      "text": "By the 90s, stats stepped in like weather forecasters predicting words from patterns in data. N-grams guessed 'next word' based on probabilities. Better, but still clunky—like autocomplete on steroids, blind to deeper meaning.",
      "title": "Stats Predict, But Don't Grasp"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter neural networks in the 2010s, brain-like webs learning from billions of sentences. RNNs read left-to-right like a slow reader, remembering context. LSTMs fixed memory leaks, but training was a slog.",
      "title": "Neural Nets Learn to Read"
    },
    {
      "text": "2017's game-changer: Transformers. Imagine eyes scanning the whole sentence at once, not word-by-word. 'Attention' mechanism weighed word importance like a spotlight on a stage. Parallel power exploded efficiency.",
      "title": "Transformers See the Big Picture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scale it up: GPT-1 (2018) sipped data; GPT-3 (2020) guzzled trillions of words on supercomputers. These giants didn't follow rules—they predicted like mimics mastering accents, generating eerily human text.",
      "title": "Birth of Language Giants"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, LLMs power your phone's voice assistant, write emails, code apps. They bridge human-AI gap, sparking creativity, but raising ethics questions. From rigid bots to fluent partners—this is AI's new era.",
      "title": "Why LLMs Reshape Our World"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture 19th-century mathematicians tossing around 'collections' like a bag of mixed marbles—no rules for what goes in or stays out. Geometry and algebra worked fine for finite stuff, but infinity? That endless beach of numbers was a wild, untamed frontier.",
      "title": "Math's Loose Collections"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter Georg Cantor, a German mathematician obsessed with infinity. He wondered: Are all infinities the same size? Like counting stars versus grains of sand on every beach—surely one's bigger? His hunch? No.",
      "title": "Infinity's Size Puzzle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cantor invented sets: precise bundles of objects, like a perfectly labeled toolbox. Suddenly, he proved some infinities dwarf others. The real numbers? An uncountably vast ocean compared to counting numbers' mere stream.",
      "title": "Cantor's Set Revolution"
    },
    {
      "text": "Triumph turned to terror. In 1901, Bertrand Russell dropped a bomb: Consider the set of all sets that don't contain themselves. Does it contain itself? Boom—contradiction! Naive sets crumbled like a house of cards.",
      "title": "Russell's Paradox Bomb"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mathematicians scrambled. What if we build sets from unbreakable axioms, like ironclad recipes in a cookbook? Zermelo and Fraenkel laid down rules in 1922, taming the chaos without paradoxes.",
      "title": "The Axiomatic Lifeline"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, set theory is math's bedrock. Every proof, algorithm, database query rests on it. In discrete math, it's your Swiss Army knife for reasoning about collections rigorously—no more slippery infinities.",
      "title": "Sets: Math's Foundation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a bustling 1950s office: clerks drowning in filing cabinets stuffed with paper records. Finding one customer's info meant hours of digging through folders—like hunting treasure in a junkyard.",
      "title": "Cabinets of Chaos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter computers! Punch cards ruled the 1940s-60s. Each card held one record, sorted in rigid stacks. Need data mid-deck? Shuffle everything like a bad solitaire game. Slow and error-prone.",
      "title": "Punch Card Pandemonium"
    },
    {
      "text": "Magnetic tapes arrived in the 50s—faster storage, but sequential access only. Retrieving info meant fast-forwarding reels like an old VHS tape, wasting hours rewinding for updates.",
      "title": "Tape Reel Tangles"
    },
    {
      "text": "By the 60s, disk drives brought random access. Flat files stored records, but no structure. Duplicates everywhere, queries required custom code—like cooking without a recipe, every time.",
      "title": "Flat Files' Messy Kitchen"
    },
    {
      "text": "Data exploded: businesses tracked millions of transactions. Old systems buckled under the weight. Hierarchic databases like IMS helped big firms but were rigid trees—change branches, risk collapse.",
      "title": "The Data Deluge Hits"
    },
    {
      "text": "1970: Edgar Codd drops a bombshell paper. Data as simple tables linked by keys—like Lego bricks snapping together. No hierarchies, just relations. Query freely, no rewiring needed!",
      "title": "Codd's Relational Revolution"
    },
    {
      "text": "1980s: Oracle births the first commercial relational DB with SQL. Suddenly, 'SELECT * FROM customers WHERE city='NYC'' pulls magic from chaos in seconds.",
      "title": "SQL Spells Data Free"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, databases power Netflix recommendations, bank balances, Google searches. Without them, our digital world grinds to a halt—like a city without roads.",
      "title": "Databases: Digital Lifelines"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture Paris in the 1860s: grand salons packed with polished paintings of gods and heroes, every brushstroke perfect, every scene frozen in time like a staged photograph. This was Academic art—rigid rules ruled the day.",
      "title": "Paris Under the Salon's Thumb"
    },
    {
      "text": "But the world was speeding up. Trains roared, factories hummed, Parisians strolled sunlit boulevards. Painters itched to capture that buzz—the fleeting play of light on water, the haze of a cafe morning. Photography stole their thunder, mimicking reality too well.",
      "title": "A World Too Fast for Old Rules"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter the rebels: Monet, Renoir, Degas, and friends. Tired of rejection slips from stuffy juries, they dreamed of plein air painting—grabbing canvases and chasing sunlight like kids after fireflies, ditching dark studios for vibrant streets.",
      "title": "Rebels Chase the Sunlight"
    },
    {
      "text": "In 1874, they launched their own show. Critics sneered at Monet's hazy harbor sunrise, dubbing it 'Impressionism.' What they mocked became the name—a fleeting vibe, not a finished photo, but raw emotion splashed in color.",
      "title": "The Mocked Masterpiece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Broken brushstrokes danced like impressionist piano keys—short, vibrant bursts capturing mood over detail. No more muddy browns; pure blues, yellows exploded on canvas, making eyes vibrate with life.",
      "title": "Colors Burst Free"
    },
    {
      "text": "From ridicule to revolution: museums filled with their work. Impressionism birthed modern art, teaching us to savor moments—the glow on a lover's face, city shimmer at dusk. Today, it shapes ads, films, your Instagram filters.",
      "title": "Echoes in Every Snapshot"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine o século XVIII: o mundo fervilhava com ideias iluministas. Filósofos como Rousseau e Voltaire debatiam a natureza humana em salões parisienses, mas era tudo especulação poética, sem método científico. A sociedade era um mistério indecifrável.",
      "title": "Sociedade como enigma filosófico"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aí veio a Revolução Industrial, como um trem desgovernado. Fábricas engoliam camponeses nas cidades sujas, crianças trabalhavam 16 horas, greves explodiam. Por que a ordem social desmoronava? Ninguém tinha ferramentas para explicar o caos humano em massa.",
      "title": "O furacão da Revolução Industrial"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pensadores como Saint-Simon sonhavam alto: e se tratássemos a sociedade como a física trata a matéria? Medir, observar, prever. Seu pupilo, Auguste Comte, pegou essa faísca e acendeu a fogueira em 1838, cunhando 'Sociologia' – o estudo científico da sociedade.",
      "title": "A faísca de Comte"
    },
    {
      "text": "Não era só teoria. Durkheim analisou suicídios como sintomas sociais, Marx dissecou classes como engrenagens em conflito, Weber explorou racionalidade como motor moderno. A Sociologia virou lente para enxergar o invisível nas relações humanas.",
      "title": "Pioneiros decifrando o social"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoje, ela explica polarizações nas redes, desigualdades urbanas, migrações globais. Sem Sociologia, seríamos cegos para as forças que moldam nosso dia a dia, como peixes ignorando a correnteza do rio.",
      "title": "Por que você precisa dela agora"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture early programmers glued to loops for every repeat. Factorials? Countdown counters. Mazes? Manual backtracking stacks. It worked, but code bloated like overpacked suitcases.",
      "title": "Loops: The Only Tool in Town"
    },
    {
      "text": "Nested problems hit hard. Family trees? You'd simulate branches with arrays, praying no overflow. Fractals or searches? Spaghetti code that tangled your brain like headphones in a pocket.",
      "title": "The Nested Nightmare"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mathematicians whispered a secret: define factorial as n times factorial(n-1), halting at 0!. Euclid sized GCDs recursively millennia ago. Elegant, like Russian dolls unpacking themselves.",
      "title": "Math's Hidden Gem"
    },
    {
      "text": "1958, John McCarthy at MIT unleashes Lisp. Functions calling themselves? Mind-blowing! No loops needed—just trust the mirror of code to reflect smaller versions until base case.",
      "title": "The Self-Calling Spark"
    },
    {
      "text": "Recursion swept computing. Tower of Hanoi? A few lines. Binary trees? Traverse with grace. What took pages of iteration now danced in recursive harmony.",
      "title": "Code Mirrors Itself"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, recursion powers JSON parsers, AI searches, quicksorts. It's your elegant knife for slicing complex puzzles—understand it, and programming feels like math magic.",
      "title": "Why Recursion Rules Now"
    }
  ]
}
